    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Death, Taxes and Simple Fairness</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lawrence Naftulin letter on June 11 editorial holds repeal of estate tax need not lead to drop in charitable giving</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 11 editorial ''A Gift to the Wealthiest'' predicts a drop in charitable giving as a result of the repeal of the estate tax. Similar doom-laden forecasts were made in the early 1980's, when the top income tax rate was slashed. Instead, personal giving rose to dramatic new heights even though the charitable deduction was ''worth'' much less to donors.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 11 editorial ''A Gift to the Wealthiest'' predicts a drop in charitable giving as a result of the repeal of the estate tax. Similar doom-laden forecasts were made in the early 1980's, when the top income tax rate was slashed. Instead, personal giving rose to dramatic new heights even though the charitable deduction was ''worth'' much less to donors.</p>
        <p>It cannot be stated often enough that charitable intentions encompass far more than mere tax avoidance.</p>
        <p>LAWRENCE  NAFTULIN  Westfield, Mass., June 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
